    <text>
        <body>
            <div type=”letter”>
                <opener><dateline><date when="1916-08-11">Aug. 11, 1916.</dateline></date>
                    <salute>Dear <persName key="harriet_monroe">Harriet</persName>:</salute></opener>
                <p>I am returning this proof of <persName key="mary_aldis" ><title key="flashlights">&quot;Flashlights&quot;</title></persName>. There are only a very few corrections, which you will see I have made.</p>
<p>In regard to the alteration you made in the last page, of course, it was perfectly unnecessary. The sentence read quite well as it was. Although I admit it was an unusual construction, I should naturally prefer to have you return to it, as the sentence as amended by you does not mean quite what I meant. If, however, it is a great trouble so to do, you can leave it. I wonder will you ever learn that my manuscripts go to you correct, after having been read over many times. However, this is a small matter, and I really do not care what you do.</p>
                <closer>Affectionately yours,</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
